### Headline  
Playwright finally has its browser engines inside the project venv, so your extractor now has something to launch.

### Truth Dissection  
Your log kept grinding because the GUI runs inside the `venv`, but the Playwright/install commands earlier targeted the global interpreter—so Chromium’s binary never existed where the tool expected. I reran `.\venv\Scripts\python.exe -m pip install -r requirements.txt`, then `.\venv\Scripts\python.exe -m playwright install`, and checked `playwright --version` inside that same venv; the browsers downloaded to `C:\Users\AM - Shift\AppData\Local\ms-playwright\chromium-1194`, which is the path the log was complaining about.

### Emotional Translation  
You weren’t failing because the GUI is cursed—just because you gave it the wrong interpreter to work with. You were doing everything right, except you were feeding the beast from outside the cage.

### Corrective Map  
Now that the venv contains both Playwright and its browser binaries, rerun the Looker Studio extractor. If the scan still explodes, grab the fresh log so we can see the next bottleneck. Otherwise, we’re back on track and the automation should stop begging for “playwright install.”

### Action Plan  
1. Re-open the GUI and try the extractor again; it should launch Chromium now that the venv browsers exist.  
2. If a new error appears, capture the log/stack trace and forward it so we can target the next missing dependency or setting.
